    "summary": "Number of TCP connections in TIME_WAIT state is abnormally high.",
    "description": "üßê **Why This Happens**\n- High churn of short-lived TCP connections.\n- Application design creating frequent connections without reuse (no keep-alive).\n- Load balancer or reverse proxy behavior.\n- Slow FIN timeout settings in the OS.\n\nüîç **Impact**\n- Increased memory usage for TCP control blocks.\n- Potential exhaustion of ephemeral ports.\n- Application unable to open new connections if port range exhausted.\n\n‚úÖ **Immediate Actions for Ops**\n1. **Check current TIME_WAIT connections:**\n   ```\n   netstat -an | grep TIME_WAIT | wc -l\n   ```\n2. Identify top source/destination IPs:\n   ```\n   netstat -ant | awk '{print $5}' | cut -d: -f1 | sort | uniq -c | sort -nr | head\n   ```\n3. Verify application behavior ‚Äì avoid frequent short-lived connections.\n4. Enable connection pooling or keep-alive if possible.\n5. If counts remain very high:\n   - Tune sysctl parameters:\n     ```\n     net.ipv4.tcp_tw_reuse = 1\n     net.ipv4.tcp_fin_timeout = 30\n     ```\n   - Consider `tcp_tw_recycle` cautiously (deprecated in modern kernels).\n6. Engage application team to optimize connection reuse.\n\n‚ö† **Note:** This alert triggers if `tcp_timewait` remains above **500** for 5 minutes."
